“It’s so verbose.”
That’s probably the number one complaint I hear whenever I talk to developers about the AWS SDK for JS/TS.
They’re not wrong.
In a typical library, you instantiate one object, call a method, and you’re done:
import Stripe from "stripe";const stripe = new Stripe(process.env.STRIPE_KEY!);
const customer = await stripe.customers.create({ email: "test@example.com" });
In the AWS SDK, you instantiate a client for the service, then instantiate a second object describing the operation you want, then hand that object to the client and unwrap what comes back:
import { S3Client, GetObjectCommand } from "@aws-sdk/client-s3";const s3 = new S3Client({ region: "us-east-1" });
const response = await s3.send(
new GetObjectCommand({ Bucket: "reports", Key: "q2-2026.csv" }),
);
const csv = await response.Body?.transformToString();
Two classes, a send(), and a stream transform. For one file.
The thing is, it’s not random. AWS did the “simple” version first. It ran half the internet for a decade.
The simplicity actually turned out to be an issue.
What the one-liner was hiding
Version 2 of the SDK worked exactly the way you’d want at the call site:
const AWS = require("aws-sdk"); // <- this line is a crimeconst s3 = new AWS.S3({ region: "us-east-1" });
const res = await s3.getObject({ Bucket: "reports", Key: "q2.csv" }).promise();
Simple. And also catastrophically expensive, for two reasons.
Reason one: that require imports every AWS service in existence. Seriously. All of them. npm install aws-sdkputs 103 MB in your node_modules (the aws-sdk package alone is 98 MB, per the registry). I bundled that snippet with esbuild (wrapped in an async main, since top-level await won’t fly in a CommonJS bundle) — one getObject call, and got a 9.77 MB minified bundle. esbuild even prints a little ⚠️ next to the output size.
Reason two is sneakier, and it’s the one that made the redesign unavoidable: in v2, s3.getObject is never implemented. Not in any source file. Go ahead, grep node_modules/aws-sdk/lib/services/s3.jsfor a getObjectdefinition. You won’t find one. The string only shows up in a few doc comments (and in a generated .d.ts, which is types, not code). The operation actually lives inside apis/s3-2006-03-01.min.json, a giant JSON description of the S3 API, under the key “GetObject”. At runtime, the SDK loops over that JSON, lowercases the first letter, and stamps methods onto the client:
// aws-sdk v2, lib/service.js - abridged
defineMethods: function defineMethods(svc) {
AWS.util.each(svc.prototype.api.operations, function (method) {
if (svc.prototype[method]) return; // hand-written helpers win
svc.prototype[method] = function (params, callback) {
return this.makeRequest(method, params, callback);
};
});
}Methods conjured out of JSON at load time are invisible to static analysis. A bundler looking at svc.prototype[method] = ... has no idea which operations your app actually uses, so it has to keep everything: the whole JSON model, the whole machinery. You cannot tree-shake methods that don't exist until runtime. The ergonomic API and dead-code elimination weren't in tension, they were simply mutually exclusive.
(v2 went into maintenance mode in September 2024 and reached end-of-support in September 2025. require(“aws-sdk”)has printed a warning at import time since early 2023. These days it flatly tells you the SDK “has reached end-of-support.”)
So in December 2020, AWS shipped v3 as a ground-up rewrite, and its core API is an implementation of one of my favorite (and oldest) patterns in the book. Literally the book.
The Command pattern
The Command pattern’s whole idea: software should sometimes work like a remote control.
A remote control doesn’t know how to turn on your TV. There’s no TV logic inside it. Each button just holds a command: a small object that knows which device it talks to and what to ask of it. The remote’s only job is to fire whatever is loaded into the slot. Add a new device to your home, and the remote never changes; you just program a new command into a button.
That’s the pattern: wrap each request in an object with one uniform interface, so the thing that triggers work is fully decoupled from the things that do the work. And once requests are objects instead of method calls, you can do things to them you can’t do to a method call: pass them around, queue them, log them, retry them, undo them, etc.
Too abstract? Consider this:
You’re building a smart-home hub
Devices keep arriving: lights, a thermostat, a door lock, and next sprint, whatever the hardware team ships. The obvious solution:
class SmartHomeHub {
// The hub must know about every device it will ever control
constructor(
private lights: Lights,
private thermostat: Thermostat,
private lock: DoorLock,
) {} run(action: string, payload?: unknown) {
console.log(`[hub] running ${action}`); // Entangled logic
switch (action) {
case "lights.on":
return this.lights.on();
case "thermostat.set":
return this.thermostat.set(payload as number);
case "door.lock":
return this.lock.lock();
// Every new device: reopen this file, add a case, redeploy the hub
default:
throw new Error(`Unknown action: ${action}`);
}
}
}
It works. It would also kind of suck in reality. The hub depends on every device (fat imports), actions are stringly-typed, payload is a lie the type system can't catch, and the switch grows forever. Every cross-cutting concern (logging, retries, permissions, etc.) gets threaded through the same swelling function.
Now the Command version:
// The "button" shape. Every command looks identical from the outside.
interface Command {
execute(): void;
}// Each operation is its own class. It knows its device and its params.
class SetTemperature implements Command {
constructor(private thermostat: Thermostat, private celsius: number) {}
execute() { this.thermostat.set(this.celsius); }
}
class LockDoor implements Command {
constructor(private lock: DoorLock) {}
execute() { this.lock.lock(); }
}
// The hub knows NOTHING about devices. Only the button shape.
class SmartHomeHub {
press(command: Command) {
console.log(`[hub] ${command.constructor.name}`); // cross-cutting, once
command.execute();
}
}
const hub = new SmartHomeHub();
hub.press(new SetTemperature(new Thermostat(), 21));
hub.press(new LockDoor(new DoorLock()));
New device? New command class. The hub never changes, and neither does anything that talks to it. Each command’s parameters are fully typed. And because commands are just values now, a “scene” falls out for free:
const goodnight: Command[] = [
new TurnLightsOff(livingRoom),
new SetTemperature(thermostat, 18),
new LockDoor(frontDoor),
];
goodnight.forEach((cmd) => hub.press(cmd));Anyone using your code knows exactly how to call it — regardless of how many commands exist, or how many are added after you ship.
Now look at the AWS SDK again
await s3.send(new GetObjectCommand({ Bucket: "reports", Key: "q2.csv" }));S3Client is the remote. GetObjectCommand is a button. send() is pressing it. Same shape across every one of the 400+ service packages, every operation, forever.
The payoffs are exactly the ones you’d want the pattern for:
1. Every command flows through one pipeline. Because there’s a single choke point (send), v3 replaced v2's mess of request-lifecycle event listeners with a proper middleware stack. Cross-cutting concerns bolt on once and apply to every operation:
s3.middlewareStack.add(
(next, context) => async (args) => {
const t0 = performance.now();
const result = await next(args);
console.log(`${context.commandName} took ${(performance.now() - t0).toFixed(1)}ms`);
return result;
},
{ step: "initialize", name: "timingMiddleware" },
);
// "GetObjectCommand took 27.9ms" - for this and every future commandRetries, SigV4 signing, checksums, your logging — all just middleware on the same stack the commands march through.
2. Commands are values, so tests become trivial. This is my favorite quiet win. With aws-sdk-client-mock, you match on the command class:
const s3Mock = mockClient(S3Client);
s3Mock.on(GetObjectCommand).resolves({
Body: sdkStreamMixin(Readable.from(["fake report"])),
});No monkey-patching prototypes, no network. You’re just intercepting objects.
3. Operations became statically analyzable, which is huge. GetObjectCommand is a real class in a real module with real imports. A bundler can finally see what you use. That's what made per-service packages possible, and tree-shaking on top of them.
The receipts
I bundled the same single getObject call four ways with esbuild (--bundle --minify --platform=node, plus ESM resolution for the v3 rows, see footnote two), on today’s versions (aws-sdk@2.1693.0, the final v2 release ever, and @aws-sdk/client-s3@3.1084.0):
v2, require("aws-sdk") 9.77 MB <- The way most v2 code was written
v2, require("aws-sdk/clients/s3") 473 KB <- The workaround few people used
v3, S3Client + GetObjectCommand 402 KB <- ESM build, tree-shaken
v3, aggregated S3 client 422 KB <- ESM build, all 112 opsThat’s a ~96% reduction against how v2 was actually used in the wild, which is in the same ballpark as AWS’s own migration workshop, where the frontend main chunk dropped from ~395 KB to ~48 KB (modular imports plus code-splitting) and simulated Fast-3G load time fell from ~17s to ~3s.
Bonus
Two honest footnotes:
Footnote one: v3 still lets you use the v2-style API. import { S3 } from "@aws-sdk/client-s3" gives you an aggregated client where s3.getObject(params) just works. AWS’s docs note the style “may be familiar to you from the AWS SDK for JavaScript v2”. So the simple pattern didn't "fail" so much as get demoted: it's now the opt-in convenience, and the command form is the recommended default. The 20 KB gap above is what carrying all 112 S3 operations costs once tree-shaking is real. Modest, because on a heavyweight client like S3, shared machinery dominates: the single biggest chunk is the API’s shape metadata (which isn’t tree-shaken per operation, both builds carry all of it), followed by endpoint rules, signing, and XML handling. The giant win came from per-service packages, which the command architecture is what made possible.
Footnote two: a gotcha that bites real Lambda deployments. With --platform=node, esbuild’s default resolution (main, then module) picks up the SDK’s CommonJS build, and CJS internals can’t be tree-shaken, so bare-bones and aggregated both weighed 547 KB in my test, 31 bytes apart. Adding --main-fields=module,main switches to the ESM build and gets you the 402/422 KB in the table. (Frontend bundlers do even better: under browser resolution the SDK swaps in lighter internals and drops the Node credential chain, and the same two bundles land at 259 KB and 279 KB.) Check your bundler config, the pattern only pays if the toolchain can see it.
The book
The Command pattern is one of the original 23 from Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software. The Gang of Four, a favorite.
Their one-line intent, paraphrased: turn a request into an object, and you can suddenly parameterize, queue, log, and undo it.
(And if my remote-control framing felt familiar: that’s the canonical teaching example from Head First Design Patterns, chapter 6: “The Command Pattern: Encapsulating Invocation.”)
Conclusion
V3 of the AWS SDK is verbose. Good. The architecture that makes it verbose is the same thing that makes it superior to v2. Thirty years on, the freshest thing about the most-downloaded SDK on npm is a pattern old enough to have a mortgage.
Next time an API makes you instantiate “one object too many”, ask yourself: is it really incompetence? Or just a remote control?
